If you want to know why LB seems like the hardest non-QB spot to draft it's because of:

- Wider hashes in college makes offensive structures different, so college LBs are basically learning a different position entirely.

- 3 yards of room for OL to work RPOs instead of 1 yard means offenses just spam them at a much higher rate than the NFL.

- There's much space and too much RPO usage to ever play a lot of spot drop zone in college, so it's mostly match coverages which means guys don't learn how to be hook droppers.
- Narrower hashes in the NFL forces passing games to be more to the middle of the field, so teams play more spot drop at that level (because they can, and it helps force turnovers).

- To expand on that, if you can only be effective in coverage when you are looking at your man instead of looking at the quarterback (because you don't know how to), then that means your DC can't call everything he wants to.

It's a different sport entirely, tbh.

All characters need to be somewhat relatable, but I don't think the Gemstones are sympathetic. The delight you get out of the kids is in knowing their faith is a Potemkin Village. And yet they succeed because of the rickety support structure built by people like their dad.

This is not new, at all, for their character type. The corrupt priest trope is as old as clay tablets. Mesopotamia, Old and New Testaments, Chaucer, Dante, Boccaccio

The "new" in this show is watching that page turn from classic grifter evangelism to late stage Capital wearing God like a skin suit.

Priests are meant to be the bridge from the material world to the spiritual. So one would use characters like these to antagonize what culture says it wants out of god, contrasted against what that actually gets you. You deploy these in moments of transition.

Sinclair Lewis writes "Elmer Gantry" during the Depression. Gantry is a greedy philanderer the same as all the other million priest characters, but he arrives when he does because Lewis is a socialist critiquing the hollowness of faith when real salvation in the form of collectivism is right there

Eli Sunday in There Will Be Blood represents another moment of transition: frontier pioneers against robber baron capitalists. It's revealed guys like Sunday are there to incubate a new social order under the rule of Plainview. The Gilded Age lays its eggs in his chest.

The 70s documentary "Marjoe" is the same transition. Marjoe was a child preacher turned hippie. He reveals that revivals work like wrestling promotions. The people running them are supply-side capitalists. His mentor wants to go to S. America to build a church with a factory out back

These characters are ironic because they're still revealers. It would be fucked up to "like" them. They show how the material world relates to the spiritual through inversion and contradiction. 

You don't have to like a protagonist just because they're a protagonist.
